See manual_full_00_README.txt for the tier legend. "Breaking out of control structures" (label/break) has no examples in manual.yml -- skipped, not fabricated.

[CC-001-equality-bool]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = . == false
INPUT = null
GOLD = false
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _ == False"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[CC-002-equality-object]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = . == {"b": {"d": (4 + 1e-20), "c": 3}, "a":1}
INPUT = {"a":1, "b": {"c": 3, "d": 4}}
GOLD = true
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _ == {'b': {'d': 4+1e-20, 'c':3}, 'a':1}"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Python dict equality already ignores key order, matches jq's object-equality rule.

[CC-003-equality-stream]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[] == 1
INPUT = [1, 1.0, "1", "banana"]
GOLD = [true, true, false, false]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [x==1 for x in _]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM. Python's `1.0 == 1` is also True and `"1" == 1` is also False (no implicit coercion) -- happens to match jq's strict-equality rule exactly here.

[CC-004-if-elif-else]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = if . == 0 then "zero" elif . == 1 then "one" else "many" end
INPUT = 2
GOLD = "many"
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= ('zero' if _==0 else ('one' if _==1 else 'many'))"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Python's chained ternary substitutes for if/elif/else -- this resolves the "is if a native JFTL construct" question from curated-batch 110 pragmatically, by not needing one.

[CC-005-comparison]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = . < 5
INPUT = 2
GOLD = true
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _ < 5"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[CC-006-and]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = 42 and "a string"
INPUT = null
GOLD = true
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= bool(42) and bool('a string')"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Wrapped in bool() since jq's and/or always yield true/false, unlike Python's and/or which return one of the operands.

[CC-007-or-stream]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = (true, false) or false
INPUT = null
GOLD = [true, false]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [bool(x or False) for x in [True, False]]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM.

[CC-008-and-cartesian]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = (true, true) and (true, false)
INPUT = null
GOLD = [true, false, true, false]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [bool(a and b) for a in [True,True] for b in [True,False]]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM. Nested comprehension reproduces jq's cartesian-product evaluation of two generator operands.

[CC-009-not]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = [true, false | not]
INPUT = null
GOLD = [false, true]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [not x for x in [True,False]]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[CC-010-alt-empty]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = empty // 42
INPUT = null
GOLD = 42
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= 42"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, constant (empty never contributes a value, so // always falls through to the right side here).

[CC-011-alt-present]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .foo // 42
INPUT = {"foo": 19}
GOLD = 19
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _.get('foo') if _.get('foo') not in (None, False) else 42"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN.

[CC-012-alt-missing]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .foo // 42
INPUT = {}
GOLD = 42
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _.get('foo') if _.get('foo') not in (None, False) else 42"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, same template as CC-011.

[CC-013-alt-generator-single]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = (false, null, 1) // 42
INPUT = null
GOLD = 1
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= next((v for v in [False, None, 1] if v not in (None, False)), 42)"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. generator next()-with-default picks the first non-false/non-null value from the 3-value generator, or falls back to 42 -- matches jq's "// on a generator produces its first non-false/null value" rule.

[CC-014-alt-per-value]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = (false, null, 1) | . // 42
INPUT = null
GOLD = [42, 42, 1]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [v if v not in (None, False) else 42 for v in [False, None, 1]]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM. Contrast with CC-013: piping through `.` first applies `// 42` independently to each value instead of to the generator as a whole -- exactly the distinction the manual calls out.

[CC-015-try-catch-message]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = try .a catch ". is not an object"
INPUT = true
GOLD = ". is not an object"
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= (_.get('a') if isinstance(_, dict) else '. is not an object')"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Type-check substitutes for exception-based try/catch (no confirmed native try/catch construct, and Python try/except is a statement, not usable inside a single expression).

[CC-016-try-suppressed-drop]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = [.[]|try .a]
INPUT = [{}, true, {"a":1}]
GOLD = [null, 1]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [x.get('a') for x in _ if isinstance(x, dict)]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. The `true` element would error on `.a` and (with no catch) gets swallowed by `empty`, dropping it entirely from the array -- the `if isinstance(x, dict)` filter reproduces that drop.

[CC-017-try-catch-error-message]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = try error("some exception") catch .
INPUT = true
GOLD = "some exception"
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= 'some exception'"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, constant (this specific try/catch always raises and catches the same literal message regardless of input).

[CC-018-optional-drop]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = [.[] | .a?]
INPUT = [{}, true, {"a":1}]
GOLD = [null, 1]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [x.get('a') for x in _ if isinstance(x, dict)]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, same template as CC-016 -- `?` is shorthand for `try`, same example restated.

[CC-019-optional-tonumber]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = [.[] | tonumber?]
INPUT = ["1", "invalid", "3", 4]
GOLD = [1, 3, 4]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [int(x) if isinstance(x,str) else x for x in _ if (isinstance(x,str) and x.lstrip('-').isdigit()) or isinstance(x,(int,float))]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Filters out values that would fail tonumber (here, "invalid") before converting the rest -- same drop-on-error pattern as CC-016/018.
